1.d5 {%02 (now black has 3 moves candidates: Be5, Bd5, cd)} {%03
 (Which forcing moves-candidates white has here? First we should calculate
checks: Ng6 and Nf7. Then we should analyse captures: Nc6, Bc6, bc. And the last forcing move - an attacking move: d5.)}
( 1.Nf7+ Bxf7 {%02 doesn't do anything} ) ( 1.Nxg6+ hxg6 {%02
 (after the sacrifice of the knight, we certainly need to look only on the
powerful attacking moves. So it makes no sense to calculate Bc6 or bc. The only really aggressive move here is d5)}
2.d5 {%02 (now black has a choice. The moves candidates are Bb2, Bd5 and bc)}
Bxb2 ( 2...Bxd5 {%02 (or cd)} 3.Qh6+ Kg8 4.Qxg7# ) 3.Qxb2+
( 3.Qh6+ Kg8 4.Qxg6+ Kh8 {=} ) Kg8 4.dxe6 {%02 and white has an advantage. We need to remember this conclusion: Ng6 gives white an advantage.}
) ( 1.Nxc6 Nxc6 2.Bxc6 {%02 the white's position here is good, but not so good as in the line Ng6. So no reason for us to resume calculating this line.}
) ( 1.Nxc4 {%02 (or bc) also doesn't give anything special for white} )
Bxd5 {%02 (or cd)} ( 1...Bxe5 2.Bxe5+ Kg8 3.dxe6 {%02 winning} )
2.Nxg6+ {%02 (it is check, so the first move we should look at)}
hxg6 3.Qh6+ Kg8 4.Qxg7# {
 Once again I want to pay your attention on this idea: we usually need to
realize ALL the forcing candidate moves BEFORE starting to calculate the lines.
Otherwise you can forget about something. And while finding the candidate moves
you should think about every move for a second. Because it helps to realize which move you should calculate first.^013^010
}
